{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Synthetic Events and the Event Object"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a user interacts with a React element, React does not attach a listener directly to that element. Instead, React attaches a single listener at the root of the document and dispatches events internally. What your handler receives is not the browser's raw "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Event"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " object — it is a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "SyntheticEvent"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": a React-managed wrapper that normalizes browser differences and exposes the same interface everywhere."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Flow from user click through browser native event, React root listener, SyntheticEvent wrapper, to your handler function",
          "title": "React Synthetic Event flow"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why React Wraps the Native Event"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Different browsers historically exposed different event APIs. React's SyntheticEvent provides a consistent interface regardless of which browser runs your app. It matches the W3C spec so your code behaves the same in Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "There are also performance benefits. Rather than attaching a listener to every interactive element, React registers a single listener at the document root (React 17+: at the root container). When an event bubbles up, React looks up the fiber tree to find which handlers to call. This means thousands of buttons can share one real DOM listener."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The SyntheticEvent Interface"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The SyntheticEvent has the same properties and methods as the native event, plus a few React-specific additions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleClick(event) {\n  // Standard Event properties\n  console.log(event.type);          // 'click'\n  console.log(event.bubbles);       // true\n  console.log(event.cancelable);    // true\n  console.log(event.timeStamp);     // ms since document load\n\n  // Target properties\n  console.log(event.target);        // the element the user clicked\n  console.log(event.currentTarget); // the element that has this handler\n\n  // Standard Event methods\n  event.preventDefault();           // stop default browser action\n  event.stopPropagation();          // stop event bubbling\n  event.stopImmediatePropagation(); // stop bubbling + same-element listeners\n\n  // React-specific\n  console.log(event.nativeEvent);   // the underlying browser Event\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "target vs currentTarget"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "These two properties are frequently confused:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.target"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the element the user actually clicked or typed in. If a "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "<button>"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " contains an "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "<svg>"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " icon and the user clicks the icon, "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.target"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " is the "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "<svg>"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.currentTarget"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the element that has the event handler attached. Always refers to the element with the React prop. This is the safe choice when you need to read a "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "data-*"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " attribute or access the form."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Button with an icon child\n<button data-id=\"42\" onClick={handleDelete}>\n  <TrashIcon />   {/* clicking here makes event.target the SVG */}\n  Delete\n</button>\n\nfunction handleDelete(event) {\n  // ❌ May be undefined if user clicks the icon\n  const id = event.target.dataset.id;\n\n  // ✅ Always the <button>, regardless of which child was clicked\n  const id = event.currentTarget.dataset.id; // '42'\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Event-Type-Specific Properties"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Different event types add their own properties on top of the base interface. Here are the most common ones."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mouse events"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleMouseEvent(event) {\n  event.clientX;    // X relative to the viewport\n  event.clientY;    // Y relative to the viewport\n  event.pageX;      // X relative to the document\n  event.pageY;      // Y relative to the document\n  event.button;     // 0=left, 1=middle, 2=right\n  event.buttons;    // bitmask of currently held buttons\n  event.ctrlKey;    // true if Ctrl was held\n  event.shiftKey;   // true if Shift was held\n  event.altKey;     // true if Alt was held\n  event.metaKey;    // true if Cmd (Mac) / Win (Win) was held\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keyboard events"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleKeyEvent(event) {\n  event.key;        // 'Enter', 'Escape', 'a', 'ArrowUp', …\n  event.code;       // physical key: 'KeyA', 'Enter', 'Space'\n  event.keyCode;    // deprecated numeric code\n  event.ctrlKey;    // true if Ctrl held (modifier keys same as mouse)\n  event.shiftKey;\n  event.altKey;\n  event.metaKey;\n  event.repeat;     // true if key is held down (auto-repeat)\n}\n// Use event.key, not event.keyCode — key is locale-aware and readable"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Input / Change events"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleChange(event) {\n  event.target.value;    // current text value (inputs, textarea, select)\n  event.target.checked;  // boolean for checkboxes and radio buttons\n  event.target.files;    // FileList for <input type=\"file\">\n  event.target.type;     // 'text', 'checkbox', 'file', …\n  event.target.name;     // name attribute — useful in generic form handlers\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Form submit event"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleSubmit(event) {\n  event.preventDefault(); // must call this to stop page reload\n  event.target;           // the <form> element\n  // Read form data via controlled state, or:\n  const data = new FormData(event.target); // uncontrolled approach\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Accessing the Native Event"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If you need something React's wrapper doesn't expose, access the underlying browser event via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "event.nativeEvent"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This is rare but occasionally needed for low-level browser APIs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleDrop(event) {\n  event.preventDefault();\n  // DataTransfer is fully on the native event in some edge cases\n  const files = event.nativeEvent.dataTransfer.files;\n  handleFiles(files);\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React 16 Pooling vs React 17+ Per-Event Objects"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In React 16 and earlier, SyntheticEvents were "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "pooled"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": after your handler returned, React would clear the event's properties and reuse the object for the next event. This meant you could not read event properties asynchronously."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// React 16 ONLY — event pooling gotcha\nfunction handleChange(event) {\n  // ❌ Will read null after the handler returns (event was recycled)\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(event.target.value), 100);\n\n  // ✅ Fix 1: read synchronously and store in a variable\n  const value = event.target.value;\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(value), 100);\n\n  // ✅ Fix 2: call persist() to opt out of pooling\n  event.persist();\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(event.target.value), 100);\n}\n\n// React 17+ — event pooling is REMOVED\n// event.persist() is a no-op; async access works fine\nfunction handleChange(event) {\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(event.target.value), 100); // safe in React 17+\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If you are on React 17 or later (the current versions), you do not need to think about pooling. If you maintain a React 16 app, store values synchronously before any async operation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Generic Form Handler Using event.target.name"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A common pattern uses a single "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "handleChange"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " function for all form fields by reading "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "event.target.name"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to identify which field changed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function RegistrationForm() {\n  const [form, setForm] = useState({\n    username: '', email: '', password: '', newsletter: false,\n  });\n\n  function handleChange(event) {\n    const { name, type, value, checked } = event.target;\n    setForm(prev => ({\n      ...prev,\n      // checkboxes use checked; everything else uses value\n      [name]: type === 'checkbox' ? checked : value,\n    }));\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <form>\n      <input name=\"username\"   value={form.username}   onChange={handleChange} />\n      <input name=\"email\"      value={form.email}      onChange={handleChange} />\n      <input name=\"password\"   value={form.password}   onChange={handleChange} type=\"password\" />\n      <input\n        name=\"newsletter\"\n        checked={form.newsletter}\n        onChange={handleChange}\n        type=\"checkbox\"\n      />\n    </form>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Preventing Default and Stopping Propagation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// preventDefault: stop the browser's default response\nfunction handleLinkClick(event) {\n  event.preventDefault();      // don't navigate\n  router.push('/dashboard');   // use the React router instead\n}\n\n// stopPropagation: stop the event from reaching parent handlers\nfunction handleCardClick() { setExpanded(true); }\nfunction handleDeleteClick(event) {\n  event.stopPropagation(); // don't expand the card when clicking Delete\n  deleteItem(id);\n}\n\n// Both together:\nfunction handleFormLinkClick(event) {\n  event.preventDefault();\n  event.stopPropagation();\n  openModal();\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Checking Modifier Keys"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mouse and keyboard events expose modifier key state, which is useful for power-user interactions like Ctrl+click to open in a new tab or Cmd+Enter to submit."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function handleItemClick(event) {\n  if (event.metaKey || event.ctrlKey) {\n    // Cmd+Click (Mac) / Ctrl+Click (Win) — open in new tab\n    window.open(`/items/${id}`, '_blank');\n  } else {\n    navigate(`/items/${id}`);\n  }\n}\n\nfunction handleTextareaKeyDown(event) {\n  if ((event.metaKey || event.ctrlKey) && event.key === 'Enter') {\n    event.preventDefault();\n    submitForm();\n  }\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Working with Focus and Blur"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Focus events have their own subtleties. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onFocus"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " fires when an element receives focus; "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onBlur"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " fires when it loses focus. React also provides "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onFocusCapture"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onBlurCapture"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for capture-phase listening."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function SearchInput() {\n  const [focused, setFocused] = useState(false);\n  const [value, setValue] = useState('');\n  const [error, setError] = useState(null);\n\n  function handleBlur(event) {\n    setFocused(false);\n    // Validate only after user leaves the field\n    if (value && !value.includes('@')) {\n      setError('Enter a valid email');\n    } else {\n      setError(null);\n    }\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <input\n        value={value}\n        onChange={e => setValue(e.target.value)}\n        onFocus={() => setFocused(true)}\n        onBlur={handleBlur}\n        style={{ outline: focused ? '2px solid blue' : undefined }}\n      />\n      {error && <p style={{ color: 'red' }}>{error}</p>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Mistakes with the Event Object"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 1: Logging the event object in React 16 and seeing empty properties"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// React 16 only\nfunction handleClick(event) {\n  console.log(event); // logs the object\n  // When you expand it in DevTools later, properties are null — pooling recycled it\n\n  // Fix: log specific values synchronously\n  console.log(event.type, event.target.textContent);\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 2: Using return false to prevent default"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In plain HTML, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "return false"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " from an event listener prevents the default action and stops propagation. In React, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "return false"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " does nothing. You must call the methods explicitly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Does nothing in React — return false is not honored\n<a href=\"/about\" onClick={() => { doSomething(); return false; }}>Link</a>\n\n// ✅ Call preventDefault explicitly\n<a href=\"/about\" onClick={e => { e.preventDefault(); doSomething(); }}>Link</a>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 3: Mixing up target and currentTarget with nested elements"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Accordion row — clicking the arrow icon should expand\n<div className=\"row\" onClick={handleExpand}>\n  <span className=\"title\">Section 1</span>\n  <svg className=\"arrow\">...</svg>  {/* clicking this: target is <svg> */}\n</div>\n\nfunction handleExpand(event) {\n  // ❌ Only works when user clicks directly on the div, not on children\n  if (event.target.className === 'row') toggle();\n\n  // ✅ currentTarget is always the <div>, regardless of which child was clicked\n  if (event.currentTarget.className === 'row') toggle();\n  // Or just toggle unconditionally — the handler is on the right element\n  toggle();\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Touch and Pointer Events" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          { "type": "text", "text": "For mobile and touch interfaces, React supports touch events (" },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onTouchStart" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onTouchMove" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onTouchEnd" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ") and the newer pointer events (" },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onPointerDown" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onPointerMove" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onPointerUp" },
          { "type": "text", "text": "). Pointer events unify mouse, touch, and stylus input." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": { "language": "jsx" },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "function DraggableBox() {\n  const [pos, setPos] = useState({ x: 100, y: 100 });\n  const [dragging, setDragging] = useState(false);\n  const startRef = useRef({ x: 0, y: 0 });\n\n  function handlePointerDown(event) {\n    event.preventDefault();\n    setDragging(true);\n    startRef.current = {\n      x: event.clientX - pos.x,\n      y: event.clientY - pos.y,\n    };\n    event.currentTarget.setPointerCapture(event.pointerId);\n  }\n\n  function handlePointerMove(event) {\n    if (!dragging) return;\n    setPos({\n      x: event.clientX - startRef.current.x,\n      y: event.clientY - startRef.current.y,\n    });\n  }\n\n  function handlePointerUp() { setDragging(false); }\n\n  return (\n    <div\n      style={{\n        position: 'absolute',\n        left: pos.x, top: pos.y,\n        width: 80, height: 80,\n        background: dragging ? '#818cf8' : '#6366f1',\n        cursor: dragging ? 'grabbing' : 'grab',\n        borderRadius: 8,\n      }}\n      onPointerDown={handlePointerDown}\n      onPointerMove={handlePointerMove}\n      onPointerUp={handlePointerUp}\n    />\n  );\n}" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Capture vs Bubble Phase" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          { "type": "text", "text": "Every event travels in two phases: first " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }], "text": "capture" },
          { "type": "text", "text": " (top-down, from document to target) then " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "bold" }], "text": "bubble" },
          { "type": "text", "text": " (bottom-up, from target back to document). All React event props (" },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onClick" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", etc.) fire in the bubble phase by default. Adding " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "Capture" },
          { "type": "text", "text": " suffix (e.g. " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onClickCapture" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ") fires in the capture phase instead." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": { "language": "jsx" },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "// onClickCapture fires BEFORE children's onClick\nfunction ActivityTracker({ children }) {\n  function handleCaptureClick(event) {\n    // Runs before any child handler\n    logActivity('click', event.target.tagName);\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <div onClickCapture={handleCaptureClick}>\n      {children}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n// Capture-phase listeners see every click in the subtree first,\n// before any bubble-phase handler on any child fires." }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          { "type": "text", "text": "Capture-phase listeners are rarely needed in application code. They are most useful for analytics, focus management, or accessibility tooling that needs to observe all events in a subtree before any component handles them." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": { "level": 2 },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "Clipboard and Drag Events" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          { "type": "text", "text": "React also wraps clipboard events (" },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onCopy" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onCut" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onPaste" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ") and drag events (" },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onDragStart" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onDragOver" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ", " },
          { "type": "text", "marks": [{ "type": "code" }], "text": "onDrop" },
          { "type": "text", "text": ")." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": { "language": "jsx" },
        "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "function DropZone({ onFileDrop }) {\n  const [over, setOver] = useState(false);\n\n  function handleDragOver(event) {\n    event.preventDefault(); // required — browser blocks drop by default\n    setOver(true);\n  }\n\n  function handleDrop(event) {\n    event.preventDefault();\n    setOver(false);\n    const files = Array.from(event.dataTransfer.files);\n    onFileDrop(files);\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <div\n      onDragOver={handleDragOver}\n      onDragLeave={() => setOver(false)}\n      onDrop={handleDrop}\n      style={{ background: over ? '#dbeafe' : '#f1f5f9', padding: 32, borderRadius: 8 }}\n    >\n      {over ? 'Release to upload' : 'Drag files here'}\n    </div>\n  );\n}" }]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "React wraps every DOM event in a SyntheticEvent that normalizes cross-browser differences."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The SyntheticEvent exposes the same properties and methods as the native event, plus "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.nativeEvent"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " for low-level access."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.currentTarget"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (not "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.target"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ") when reading data from the element that has the handler."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Call "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.preventDefault()"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " explicitly — "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "return false"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " has no effect in React."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "React 16: event properties are nulled after the handler returns (pooling); store values synchronously. React 17+: pooling is gone."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Mouse events expose clientX/Y, button, and modifier keys; keyboard events expose "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "event.key"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (prefer over deprecated keyCode)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
